│ instruction asserts that none of its operands are NaNs. If an operand *is* a NaN, the      │
│ instruction's result is `poison`. In the provided reproducer, the outer `copysign` call    │
│ has the `nnan` flag.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe `opt` log shows the            │
│ transformation:\n```\nIC: Mod =   %r = call nnan nsz float @llvm.copysign.f32(float %x,    │
│ float %s)\n    New =   %r = call nnan nsz float @llvm.copysign.f32(float %x, float         │
│ %z)\n```\nThis confirms that `instcombine` is replacing `%s` with `%z` as the second       │
│ argument to the outer `copysign` call. The `nnan` flag from the original instruction `%r`  │
│ is preserved in the new instruction.\n\nThe Alive2 verification tool provides a            │
│ counterexample that exposes the flaw:\n- `%x = +0.0`\n- `%y = +0.0`\n- `%z =               │
│ QNaN`\n\n**Source Execution:**\n1.  `%s = copysign(%y, %z)`: `copysign(+0.0, QNaN)`. The   │
│ inner `copysign` does *not* have the `nnan` flag. It correctly produces `+0.0` (magnitude  │
│ of `%y`, sign of `%z`).\n2.  `%r = copysign(%x, %s)`: `copysign(+0.0, +0.0)`. This is the  │
│ outer call, which *does* have the `nnan` flag. Since its operands (`%x` and `%s`) are not  │
│ NaNs, it executes correctly and returns `+0.0`.\n\n**Target Execution:**\n1.  `%r =        │
│ copysign(%x, %z)`: `copysign(+0.0, QNaN)`. The new instruction inherits the `nnan` flag.   │
│ Since one of its operands (`%z`) is a NaN, the `nnan` contract is violated, and the result │
│ becomes `poison`.\n\nThe transformation is incorrect because it changes a valid            │
│ computation (resulting in `+0.0`) into one that produces `poison`.\n\n### 3. Root Cause    │
│ Analysis\n\nThe issue lies in the `visitCallInst` function within `InstCombineCalls.cpp`.  │
│ The code attempts to simplify `copysign(Mag, copysign(Y, Sgn))`. It correctly identifies   │
│ that the sign is determined by `Sgn` and replaces the second argument.\n\nHowever, the     │
│ code fails to consider the implications of the `nnan` flag. The original second operand,   │
│ `copysign(Y, Sgn)`, might produce a non-NaN value even if `Sgn` is a NaN. By substituting  │
│ `Sgn` directly into the outer `copysign` call, the optimization exposes the outer call to  │
│ a potential NaN operand that was previously shielded. The check for the validity of this   │
│ transformation is insufficient.\n\nThe relevant code snippet is:\n```cpp\n// copysign(Mag, │
│ copysign(Y, Sgn)) -> copysign(Mag, Sgn)\nif (auto *CS = dyn_cast<CallInst>(Op1)) {\n  if   │
│ (CS->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::copysign && CS->hasOneUse()) {\n    if (Op0->getType() │
│ == CS->getArgOperand(1)->getType()) {\n      CI.setArgOperand(1, CS->getArgOperand(1));\n  │
│ return &CI;\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\nThis logic needs to be more conservative. It should only  │
│ perform the transformation if it can prove that doing so will not introduce a `poison`     │
│ value due to the `nnan` flag. The simplest, safest condition is to disable this            │
│ optimization if the outer `copysign` call has the `nnan` flag.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit     │
│ Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to add a check for the `nnan` flag on the outer `copysign` call     │
│ (`CI`) and prevent the optimization if the flag is present.\n\n**File**:                   │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCalls.cpp`\n\n```cpp\n---                      │
│ a/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCalls.cpp\n+++                                │
│ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCalls.cpp\n@@ -2700,6 +2700,10 @@\n   //      │
│ copysign(Mag, copysign(Y, Sgn)) -> copysign(Mag, Sgn)\n   if (auto *CS =                   │
│ dyn_cast<CallInst>(Op1)) {\n     if (CS->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::copysign &&        │
│ CS->hasOneUse()) {\n+      // This is not valid if the outer copysign has nnan, because    │
│ the inner\n+      // copysign might be hiding a NaN.\n+      if (CI.hasNoNaNs())\n+        │
│ return nullptr;\n       if (Op0->getType() == CS->getArgOperand(1)->getType()) {\n         │
│ CI.setArgOperand(1, CS->getArgOperand(1));\n         return &CI;\n\n```\n\n### 5.          │
│ Conclusion\n\nThe proposed edit corrects the miscompilation by adding a necessary guard to │
│ the `copysign(copysign)` optimization. By checking for the `nnan` flag on the outer call,  │
│ we ensure the transformation is only applied when it is safe to do so, preventing the      │
│ introduction of `poison` values and preserving the program's semantics. This small change  │
│ makes the optimization more robust and corrects the bug reported."                         │
│ }                                                                                          │
